            <biogHist>
                <p>Duncan MacDiarmaid was born in Duirinish, the son of Malcolm MacDiarmaid,
                    shepherd, and Effie MacDiarmaid n√©e Cameron. By the time he crossed paths with
                    Alexander Carmichael in 1861 he was living with his family in Fernilea,
                    Bracadale; Carmichael collected several stories from him there, over a number of
                    visits. After then MacDiarmid appears to have followed work around the country,
                    as no two census returns give the same place of residence; by 1871 he was lodged
                    near Stirling while working as a shepherd, and by 1879 was living in Glasgow as
                    a Clyde Trust bargeman. His marriage to Annie Cameron, a Bracadale native
                    working as a domestic servant in Park Circus, Glasgow, took place in 1879 in the
                    Free Church on Maclellan Street, Govan; by the 1881 census they were living
                    together with their young son (6 months) and a boarder at Berkley Street,
                    Glasgow. </p>
                <p>Tragically his death came in the same year, back in Fernilea again, with the
                    cause of death recorded as pulmonary phthisis an illness he had suffered from
                    for 2 years. His death certificate was signed by his father-in-law Malcolm
                    Cameron. </p>
